<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet xml:id="sec-fin-rev">
        <title>Final Review Information</title>
        <exercise workspace="8in">
            <title>Final Review</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The following comments and conceptual questions are intended to help you review important ideas covered on the final.
                    You should use them, along with portfolio questions and the midterms to guide your studying and creation
                    of a single note sheet that can be used during the in-class final. I consider the creation of a note sheet for a 
                    cumulative final like this a very important part of your studying. Focus on the quality of what will actually help you,
                    not on the quantity. What concepts were emphasized on the midterms? What did you struggle with most?  
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                              Midterm 1 material: the midterm itself is the best resource to guide your review. The topics from the midterm
                              that were either the most widely missed or the most widely used in our course (and thus the most important for
                              assessing) are
                              <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Proofs regarding injectivity/surjectivity of functions (particularly under composition). See problem 4 
                                        of midterm 1.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Set arguments to show one set is contained in another. See problems 2 and 5 of midterm 1.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Understanding the Completeness Axiom, and proving properties and uniqueness of supremums/infimums. See 
                                        problems 6, 7, and 8 of midterm 1.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Understanding basic properties of the real numbers. See problem 9 of midterm 1.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                              </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                              Midterm 2 material: the midterm itself is the best resource to guide your review. The topics from the midterm
                              that were either the most widely missed or the most widely used in our course (and thus the most important for
                              assessing) are
                              <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Identifying open, closed, compact, and connected sets, and identifying accumulation points
                                        of sets. See problem 1 of midterm 2.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Proving the monotone convergence theorem. See problems 3 of midterm 2.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                       Justifying that a function is discontinuous using various characterizations of 
                                       continuity (particularly the epsilon-delta characterization and the characterization
                                       using preimages). See problem 5 of midterm 2.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Using the extreme value theorem and the intermediate value theorem. See problem 6 of 
                                        midterm 2.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                              </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                New Material: topics from chapters 8 and 9 to focus on are 
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            Knowing and using the limit definition of derivative to determine if a function
                                            is differentiable at a point.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            Understanding the relationship between differentiability and continuity.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            Using the mean value theorem.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            Computing upper and lower sums for a function for a given partition (both regular 
                                            and not regular).
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            Determining whether a function is integrable on a given interval by thinking 
                                            about upper and lower integrals.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            Knowing particular classes of functions that we have proven are always integrable 
                                            on a closed bounded interval.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            Knowing and using the fundamental theorem of calculus (recall there are 2 statements!).
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

            </statement>
            
        </exercise>
      

        </worksheet>
    </article>
</pretext>